{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487180"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:00:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:00:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"272"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/272"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.65,0.14,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113180"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/272"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95207"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14136"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45657"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113180"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute onset left-sided abdominal pain associated with nausea. Her last menstrual period was two weeks ago but she has noticed some abnormal \u0022spotting\u0022 today. She is sexually active and takes the progesterone only pill for contraception. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any other regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is tenderness in the left iliac fossa. There is no guarding or rigidity. The speculum examination is unremarkable. A bimanual examination reveals left adnexal tenderness. A urinary beta-hCG is negative. Her complete blood picture and biochemistry are normal. Haemoglobin is 135 g/L (115-165). A transvaginal ultrasound is performed which demonstrates no ovarian torsion, but several small ovarian cysts bilaterally. The largest cyst is 25mm in diameter and there is a small amount of simple free fluid in the pouch of douglas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Morphine IV","Antibiotics and observation","Paracetamol + ibuprofen PO","Urgent laparoscopic cystectomy","Combined oral contraceptive pill"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation of acute lower abdominal pain, a negative b-hCG and the ultrasound findings are consistent with an ovarian cyst rupture. These patients are typically managed conservatively with a focus on \u003Cstrong\u003Eanalgesia\u003C/strong\u003E. The WHO pain ladder advises pain control with simple analgesics such as NSAIDs and \u003Cstrong\u003Eparacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E. Opioids are usually reserved for severe pain and/or cancer pain. Hence, \u003Cstrong\u003Emorphine\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf similar episodes recur, they might need suppression of ovulation with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehormonal contraception\u003C/strong\u003E However, since this is the first time the patient presented with such symptoms there is no clear indication to recommend commencing hormonal contraception unless the patient wishes to for another reason (such as contraception).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients who are haemodynamically unstable may proceed to surgery to achieve haemostasis via suturing, cautery, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E, or - less commonly - salpingo-oophorectomy. Since the patient has normal blood pressure, pulse and no signs of anaemia, we would not proceed with surgical treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotics and observation\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there was concern for pelvic inflammatory disease or tubo-ovarian abscess. However, this patient has no fever, normal white cell count, and the ultrasound shows simple cysts without features of infection. The clinical picture is most consistent with cyst rupture rather than infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of simple ovarian cyst rupture can be managed with conservative measures."],"references":["Bottomley, C, Bourne, T. Diagnosis and management of ovarian cyst accidents. 2009; 23: 711-24.","Anekar AA, Cascella M. WHO Analgesic Ladder. [Updated 2023 Jan 29]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554435/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95207"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"272"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95207"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T10:37:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T10:37:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"272"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113180"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"descriptio